nglicized as   Mangan  .","English: from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Manning</i>.","North German and Dutch: habitational name from a farm so named, once in possession of a certain <i>Manno</i> (see   Mann   2) and his kin."],"variants":[{"name":"Mannen","meanings":["Altered form of Irish or English   Manning  ."]},{"name":"Mannion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Malachy, Brendan, Aislinn, Brigid, Ciaran, Declan, Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Maeve, Siobhan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mainnín</b> (see   Manning  ).","English and Irish: variant of   Mangan  ."]},{"name":"Mangan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Declan.","Irish: from <b>Ó Maingín</b>, see   Mannion  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mongáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mongán</i>’, a byname for someone with a luxuriant head of hair (from <i>mong</i> ‘hair, mane’)."]},{"name":"Mannings","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donovan, Eamonn, Ronan.","Irish: variant of   Manning   1, with the addition of English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady 